# Git-only deployment

**Never** deploy by copying files onto the server (`scp`, `rsync`, `tar | ssh`, editing `/opt/pisster` outside git, or rebuilding from an unclean tree).

## Standard deploy (app / web code)

From the **local** repo:

1. Commit and `git push origin HEAD` (only when the user asks to commit/deploy).
2. On the server (`/opt/pisster`):

```bash
git fetch origin
git reset --hard origin/main   # clean tree; must match pushed commit
docker compose run --rm migrate   # only if there are new Prisma migrations
docker compose up -d --build --force-recreate --no-deps web
```

Rebuild **only `web`** for Next.js / app changes. Do **not** recreate `nginx`, `postgres`, `redis`, `caddy`, or workers unless their config/image actually changed.

## When nginx config changed

Only if `nginx/` or nginx-related `.env` keys (`SITE_SERVER_NAMES`, `NETWORK_REFERERS`, …) changed:

```bash
docker compose up -d --force-recreate --no-deps nginx
```

Prefer this **after** `web` is healthy. Recreating nginx too often caused intermittent `web could not be resolved` 502s historically.

## Verify after deploy

```bash
# App (bypass client DNS): should be 200
curl -sS -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\n' --resolve admin.sharlila.com:443:3.224.159.145 https://admin.sharlila.com/login
curl -sS -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\n' https://pisster.com/

# DNS (authoritative / public): should show the server A record
dig +short @8.8.8.8 admin.sharlila.com A
```

Server git must be clean and at the same commit as `origin/main`.

## `DNS_PROBE_FINISHED_NXDOMAIN` on admin.sharlila.com

Deploy does **not** change Route 53 and does **not** delete the A record. The app can be healthy while the browser shows NXDOMAIN.

**Why it feels like “deploy broke DNS”:** the A record TTL is **300s**. A deploy (build + recreate) often takes longer than that. While you wait, the browser/OS positive cache expires; the next lookup goes to the LAN/ISP resolver (e.g. router `192.168.1.1`), which may still have a **stale NXDOMAIN** from before `admin.sharlila.com` existed. So: worked (cached A) → deploy wait → NXDOMAIN (bad recursive cache). Public resolvers stay fine the whole time.

**Proof checklist (run when Chrome shows NXDOMAIN):**

```bash
dig +short @8.8.8.8 admin.sharlila.com A          # expect 3.224.159.145
dig +short @192.168.1.1 admin.sharlila.com A      # often empty/NXDOMAIN on home router
curl -sS -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}\n' \
  --resolve admin.sharlila.com:443:3.224.159.145 \
  https://admin.sharlila.com/login                 # expect 200 → app/deploy OK
```

**What to do:** use `8.8.8.8` / `1.1.1.1` on the client or router, reboot/flush the router DNS cache, or wait for negative cache to expire. Do **not** “fix” it with scp or a full stack recreate.

SOA negative-cache minimum for `sharlila.com` was lowered to **300s** so new NXDOMAIN answers expire faster; resolvers that already cached the old 24h NXDOMAIN must still age that out or be flushed.

## Forbidden

- Hotfixing production outside git
- Leaving the server worktree dirty as source of truth
- Recreating nginx/caddy/postgres on every web deploy
- Assuming browser NXDOMAIN means the deploy broke the app
